00:50:08,047 --> 00:50:09,132
- I'm trying to.
- Right.

1016
00:50:09,340 --> 00:50:10,882
Well, happens to be a rather...

1017
00:50:11,050 --> 00:50:12,092
...confidential sort of thing...

1018
00:50:12,300 --> 00:50:13,719
...but you might make
a nice bit of money.

1019
00:50:13,927 --> 00:50:16,514
- No, thank you. I have my hands full.
- You wouldn't have to do...

1020
00:50:16,681 --> 00:50:18,181
...any business with Wolfshiem,
I assure you.

1021
00:50:18,391 --> 00:50:20,476
It's a favor, Jay. Just a favor.

1022
00:50:23,186 --> 00:50:25,523
Yes. Happy to do it.

1023
00:50:26,106 --> 00:50:27,692
- Favor?
- Yes.

1024
00:50:29,360 --> 00:50:30,485
Hm.

1025
00:50:32,864 --> 00:50:33,655
Well, good night.

1026
00:50:33,864 --> 00:50:35,449
Good night.

1027
00:50:41,998 --> 00:50:43,750
[CHATTERING]

1028
00:50:53,885 --> 00:50:55,302
Good morning.

1029
00:50:59,474 --> 00:51:01,893
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

1030
00:51:23,498 --> 00:51:26,458
One of the papers says they thought
the rain would stop about 4.

1031
00:51:28,335 --> 00:51:31,047
I think it was the...
I think it was the Journal.

1032
00:51:31,213 --> 00:51:32,422
Ah.

1033
00:51:34,342 --> 00:51:36,135
GATSBY: Just in to the right, gentlemen.
To the right...

1034
00:51:36,344 --> 00:51:37,719
...in the living room. Thank you.

1035
00:51:43,184 --> 00:51:44,976
Is everything all right?

1036
00:51:45,186 --> 00:51:46,603
NICK: The grass looks fine,
if that's what you mean.

1037
00:51:47,896 --> 00:51:48,563
Grass?

1038
00:51:49,023 --> 00:51:50,900
What grass?

1039
00:51:54,487 --> 00:51:56,155
I bought cakes.

1040
00:51:58,032 --> 00:52:00,117
[TICKING]

1041
00:52:07,541 --> 00:52:08,208
Have you--

1042
00:52:08,416 --> 00:52:09,668
Have you got everything you need?

1043
00:52:10,168 --> 00:52:11,628
Perhaps more flowers.

1044
00:52:12,963 --> 00:52:14,882
I think they did a fine job, don't you?

1045
00:52:15,090 --> 00:52:16,342
Beautiful.

1046
00:52:16,717 --> 00:52:18,302
You think it's too much?

1047
00:52:18,844 --> 00:52:21,472
Uh, I think it's what you want.

1048
00:52:22,014 --> 00:52:23,766
I think so too.

1049
00:52:24,641 --> 00:52:26,226
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

1050
00:52:45,663 --> 00:52:46,329
I can't...

1051
00:52:46,539 --> 00:52:47,789
...wait all day.

1052
00:52:48,248 --> 00:52:49,291
I'm leaving.

1053
00:52:49,500 --> 00:52:51,251
Don't be silly. It's two minutes to 4.

1054
00:52:51,460 --> 00:52:52,795
No one's coming to tea! It's too--

1055
00:52:52,961 --> 00:52:53,670
[CAR HORN HONKS]

1056
00:53:02,012 --> 00:53:03,264
It's her!

1057
00:53:17,527 --> 00:53:20,155
Is this absolutely where you live,
my dearest one?

1058
00:53:20,364 --> 00:53:21,282
NICK:
Yes, it suits me.

1059
00:53:22,324 --> 00:53:23,159
<i>DAISY:
Why did I have...

1060
00:53:23,367 --> 00:53:25,827
...to come alone? Are you in love with me?

1061
00:53:26,036 --> 00:53:28,121
<i>NICK:
Oh, it's the secret of Carraway Castle.

1062
00:53:28,331 --> 00:53:31,083
- Tell your chauffeur to go far away.
- Come back in an hour...

1063
00:53:31,291 --> 00:53:32,418
...Ferdie.

1064
00:53:32,626 --> 00:53:33,960
His name is Ferdie.

1065
00:53:40,092 --> 00:53:41,469
[GASPS]

1066
00:53:41,635 --> 00:53:42,802
DAISY:
Oh.

1067
00:53:46,306 --> 00:53:49,601
Oh. My goodness.

1068
00:53:49,809 --> 00:53:52,146
I can't believe it.

1069
00:53:53,396 --> 00:53:57,108
You... Did you ransack a greenhouse?

1070
00:53:58,068 --> 00:54:00,237
He is in love with me.

1071
00:54:14,376 --> 00:54:15,043
Would you?

1072
00:54:16,045 --> 00:54:17,003
That's funny.

1073
00:54:17,213 --> 00:54:18,505
What's funny?

1074
00:54:20,173 --> 00:54:21,259
[RAPPING ON DOOR]

1075
00:54:22,385 --> 00:54:23,385
Ah.

1076
00:54:27,556 --> 00:54:28,474
What are you doing?

1077
00:55:19,650 --> 00:55:22,402
I'm certainly glad to see you again.

1078
00:55:24,739 --> 00:55:27,490
Hi. I'm...

1079
00:55:27,657 --> 00:55:30,452
I'm certainly glad to see you, as well.

1080
00:55:38,585 --> 00:55:40,463
[WATER BOILING]

1081
00:55:58,606 --> 00:56:00,523
We've... We've...

1082
00:56:01,442 --> 00:56:02,318
We've met before.

1083
00:56:06,155 --> 00:56:08,490
I'll have someone come repair this...

1084
00:56:08,699 --> 00:56:09,909
...immediately.

1085
00:56:26,217 --> 00:56:28,052
Sorry about the clock.

1086
00:56:28,927 --> 00:56:30,721
- That's an old clock.
- Lovely, though.

1087
00:56:30,929 --> 00:56:32,389
- A lovely clock.
- Yes.

1088
00:56:34,557 --> 00:56:36,059
We haven't met for many years.

1089
00:56:36,268 --> 00:56:37,894
Five years next November.

1090
00:56:40,856 --> 00:56:41,815
Tea?

1091
00:56:42,023 --> 00:56:43,943
- Yes, thank you, old sport.
- Thank you.

1092
00:56:44,193 --> 00:56:45,777
NICK: Lemon or sugar?
- Neither.

1093
00:56:46,027 --> 00:56:47,530
Plain. Thank you.

1094
00:57:06,215 --> 00:57:07,215
I just have to pop...

1095
00:57:07,382 --> 00:57:08,300
-...into town.
- Town?

1096
00:57:08,509 --> 00:57:09,385
I'll be right back.

1097
00:57:09,592 --> 00:57:10,552
Nick, I've...

1098
00:57:10,719 --> 00:57:11,469
...gotta speak to you.

1099
00:57:11,679 --> 00:57:14,181
NICK: Yes. I'll be right back.
GATSBY: God.

1100
00:57:14,389 --> 00:57:17,016
This was a mistake.
This was a terrible, terrible mistake.

1101
00:57:17,226 --> 00:57:18,936
You're just embarrassed.
Daisy's embarrassed too.

1102
00:57:21,771 --> 00:57:23,440
- She's embarrassed?
- Yes.

1103
00:57:23,648 --> 00:57:24,400
Just as much as you are.

1104
00:57:24,608 --> 00:57:25,860
- Don't talk so loud.
- Hey.

1105
00:57:26,068 --> 00:57:28,903
You're acting like a little boy.
You're being rude. Daisy's...

1106
00:57:29,112 --> 00:57:30,864
-...in there all alone and you're--
- Shh.

1107
00:58:06,317 --> 00:58:08,818
<i>NICK:
Looking over my story so far...

1108
00:58:08,985 --> 00:58:13,324
<i>...I'm reminded that
for the second time that summer...

1109
00:58:13,490 --> 00:58:16,619
<i>...I was guarding other people's secrets.

1110
00:58:17,869 --> 00:58:20,873
<i>Once again, I was within...

1111
00:58:21,581 --> 00:58:23,208
...and without.

1112
00:58:23,541 --> 00:58:25,878
[DAISY AND GATSBY
CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

1113
00:58:29,923 --> 00:58:30,798
[RATTLING]

1114
00:58:48,358 --> 00:58:49,610
NICK:
Ahem!

1115
00:58:51,445 --> 00:58:52,987
It's stopped raining.

1116
00:58:56,824 --> 00:58:57,952
GATSBY:
Yes.

1117
00:58:58,327 --> 00:58:59,786
It has, hasn't it?

1118
00:59:12,215 --> 00:59:14,092
What do you think of that, Daisy?

1119
00:59:16,344 --> 00:59:17,387
Come look.

1120
00:59:17,887 --> 00:59:20,014
DAISY:
Oh, Nicky. How funny.

1121
00:59:21,641 --> 00:59:23,851
Look, it's my house.

1122
00:59:26,771 --> 00:59:28,856
Just there across the bay.

1123
00:59:35,030 --> 00:59:36,364
GATSBY:
I know.

1124
00:59:38,032 --> 00:59:40,619
I have the same view from my place.

1125
00:59:42,204 --> 00:59:43,329
Where's your place?

1126
00:59:46,416 --> 00:59:47,083
Nick...

1127
00:59:48,585 --> 00:59:52,213
...I want you and Daisy to come over
to my house. I'd like to show her around.

1128
00:59:52,422 --> 00:59:53,882
You sure you want me to come?

1129
00:59:54,090 --> 00:59:56,260
Absolutely, old sport.

1130
00:59:56,719 --> 00:59:58,387
Absolutely.

1131
00:59:59,929 --> 01:00:01,347
Ladner, open the gates.

1132
01:00:01,556 --> 01:00:02,557
LADNER:
Open the gates!

1133
01:00:02,766 --> 01:00:05,184
I had the gates brought in
from a castle in Normandy.

1134
01:00:08,105 --> 01:00:08,771
Oh, Jay.

1135
01:00:08,981 --> 01:00:10,690
-It's so grand.
GATSBY: You like it?

1136
01:00:12,818 --> 01:00:13,485
I love it.

1137
01:00:14,737 --> 01:00:16,030
But how do you live here...

1138
01:00:16,237 --> 01:00:18,157
-...all alone?
- Well, I don't.

1139
01:00:18,364 --> 01:00:22,702
I keep it always full of
interesting, celebrated people.

1140
01:00:23,746 --> 01:00:25,204
Come with me.

1141
01:00:30,210 --> 01:00:31,795
The house looks well, doesn't it?

1142
01:00:32,003 --> 01:00:34,047
See the way the whole front
catches the light like that?

1143
01:00:34,213 --> 01:00:35,715
Oh, it's splendid.

1144
01:00:39,135 --> 01:00:40,679
DAISY:
Come on, you two. I want...

1145
01:00:40,846 --> 01:00:41,512
...the royal tour.

1146
01:00:41,679 --> 01:00:44,432
You must understand that I like all things
that are modern. Presses the orange...

1147
01:00:44,641 --> 01:00:46,476
...it all comes out there.

1148
01:00:53,900 --> 01:00:55,402
NICK:
Yay!

1149
01:00:55,943 --> 01:00:57,195
GATSBY:
Anyone for a round of golf?

1150
01:00:57,403 --> 01:01:00,865
DAISY: You do know I'm a champion golfer?
- Great!

1151
01:01:01,074 --> 01:01:02,201
GATSBY:
Well, go on.

1152
01:01:02,367 --> 01:01:03,202
I thought we could...

1153
01:01:03,452 --> 01:01:05,329
GATSBY: Remarkable little camera.
Latest design.

1154
01:01:05,536 --> 01:01:06,954
DAISY:
I'll show you how it's done.

1155
01:01:07,164 --> 01:01:08,456
GATSBY: Nick, keep filming.
NICK: All right.

1156
01:01:08,666 --> 01:01:09,541
GATSBY: She's gonna take a swing.
NICK: I'm ready.

1157
01:01:09,750 --> 01:01:11,126
Aim. Fore!

1158
01:01:14,088 --> 01:01:15,047
DAISY:
I'm such a brute.

1159
01:01:15,255 --> 01:01:17,340
NICK: You ready for your close-up?
- I don't want to forget...

1160
01:01:17,507 --> 01:01:18,592
...a single moment.
NICK: You're shimmering.

1161
01:01:18,800 --> 01:01:20,719
GATSBY: She looks like she could be
on the cover of Vogue.

1162
01:01:20,927 --> 01:01:21,929
DAISY:
Turn on the camera!

1163
01:01:23,972 --> 01:01:26,266
NICK: Where did you go?
GATSBY: Slow down.

1164
01:01:26,891 --> 01:01:27,893
Slow down.

1165
01:01:32,481 --> 01:01:33,815
DAISY:
Ahh.

1166
01:01:34,400 --> 01:01:35,067
It's beautiful.

1167
01:01:35,650 --> 01:01:37,485
GATSBY: It's a custom Wurlitzer.
DAISY: Can anyone...

1168
01:01:37,735 --> 01:01:38,778
...play that?

1169
01:01:38,945 --> 01:01:40,364
Klipspringer can. Someone wake Ewing.

1170
01:01:40,530 --> 01:01:42,615
- Of course, sir.
DAISY: Music!

1171
01:01:42,824 --> 01:01:43,659
And then we can dance...

1172
01:01:43,826 --> 01:01:46,161
...all night.
GATSBY: Ewing's a genius, plays anything.

1173
01:01:46,577 --> 01:01:49,081
DAISY: Then I demand a Charleston.
- She makes it look so splendid...

1174
01:01:49,289 --> 01:01:50,916
...don't you think, old sport?

1175
01:01:53,293 --> 01:01:54,503
GATSBY:
I have a man in England...

1176
01:01:54,711 --> 01:01:56,130
...who buys me clothes.

1177
01:01:56,422 --> 01:01:57,965
DAISY:
I've never seen anything like it.

1178
01:01:58,172 --> 01:01:59,215
Something for the lady.

1179
01:02:00,217 --> 01:02:01,719
He sends over a selection at...

1180
01:02:01,927 --> 01:02:02,927
...the beginning of each season.

1181
01:02:04,804 --> 01:02:05,556
These are silk.

1182
01:02:05,764 --> 01:02:07,599
DAISY: Jay!
GATSBY: These are flannel.

1183
01:02:07,766 --> 01:02:09,351
DAISY:
They're so beautiful!

1184
01:02:09,559 --> 01:02:10,309
GATSBY:
Indian cotton.

1185
01:02:10,518 --> 01:02:12,146
DAISY:
Stop it. Jay!

1186
01:02:12,353 --> 01:02:13,605
Linen.

1187
01:02:14,021 --> 01:02:14,690
Nicky...

1188
01:02:14,856 --> 01:02:16,442
...he's a madman!
NICK: I can't help you!

1189
01:02:16,733 --> 01:02:17,400
GATSBY:
Flannel!

1190
01:02:17,650 --> 01:02:18,902
DAISY:
You're going to have to refold...

1191
01:02:19,110 --> 01:02:19,987
...every single one of them.

1192
01:02:21,237 --> 01:02:22,030
You'll ruin them!

1193
01:02:23,157 --> 01:02:24,074
[DAISY GIGGLES]

1194
01:02:26,034 --> 01:02:26,827
Jay! Stop it.

1195
01:02:27,869 --> 01:02:28,911
GATSBY: Right here!
DAISY: No!

1196
01:02:29,204 --> 01:02:30,289
Jay!

1197
01:02:35,251 --> 01:02:36,295
[DAISY CRIES]

1198
01:02:47,222 --> 01:02:48,306
What is it?

1199
01:02:50,976 --> 01:02:53,728
Daisy, Daisy, darling, what is it?

1200
01:02:58,608 --> 01:03:00,443
It makes me sad.

1201
01:03:02,653 --> 01:03:03,489
Why?

1202
01:03:03,947 --> 01:03:05,490
<i>Because...

1203
01:03:09,077 --> 01:03:11,204
NICK:
Five lost years...

1204
01:03:11,413 --> 01:03:13,873
<i>...struggled on Daisy's lips.

1205
01:03:15,125 --> 01:03:18,003
<i>But all she could manage was:

1206
01:03:20,463 --> 01:03:21,757
Why?

1207
01:03:23,967 --> 01:03:26,719
Because I've never seen
such beautiful shirts before.

1208
01:03:48,367 --> 01:03:50,619
If it wasn't for the mist...

1209
01:03:51,202 --> 01:03:53,496
...we could see the green light.

1210
01:03:59,085 --> 01:04:00,963
What green light?

1211
01:04:02,172 --> 01:04:03,715
The one that burns all night...

1212
01:04:03,923 --> 01:04:05,800
...at the end of your dock.

1213
01:04:09,012 --> 01:04:09,721
<i>NICK:
Possibly...

1214
01:04:09,929 --> 01:04:12,099
<i>...it had occurred to Gatsby that...

1215
01:04:12,306 --> 01:04:14,518
<i>...the colossal significance
of that light...

1216
01:04:14,726 --> 01:04:16,769
<i>...had vanished forever.

1217
01:04:17,603 --> 01:04:19,648
<i>Now it was once again...

1218
01:04:19,856 --> 01:04:20,983
<i>...just a green light on a dock.

1219
01:04:21,148 --> 01:04:25,570
<i>And his count of enchanted objects
had diminished by one.

1220
01:04:27,447 --> 01:04:28,114
Who's this?

1221
01:04:28,322 --> 01:04:29,699
- Your father?
GATSBY: Oh, no.

1222
01:04:29,907 --> 01:04:31,702
That's Mr. Dan Cody, old sport.

1223
01:04:33,077 --> 01:04:34,413
He's dead now.

1224
01:04:34,621 --> 01:04:37,039
He used to be my best friend
many years ago.

1225
01:04:37,958 --> 01:04:38,876
DAISY:
You never told me...

1226
01:04:39,083 --> 01:04:40,918
...you had a pompadour. Or a yacht.

1227
01:04:41,378 --> 01:04:42,838
I wanna show you something.

1228
01:04:44,840 --> 01:04:46,257
Have a seat.

1229
01:04:46,967 --> 01:04:48,885
These are a lot of clippings I collected.

1230
01:04:50,262 --> 01:04:51,679
About you.

1231
01:04:55,141 --> 01:04:56,518
DAISY:
You saved my letters.

1232
01:04:58,061 --> 01:04:59,438
This was my first...

1233
01:04:59,646 --> 01:05:00,856
...photo of you.

1234
01:05:02,356 --> 01:05:03,025
You remember...

1235
01:05:03,190 --> 01:05:05,402
...this letter here?
DAISY: We can't lose each other...

1236
01:05:05,568 --> 01:05:06,612
...and let all this...

1237
01:05:06,777 --> 01:05:07,612
<i>...glorious love...

1238
01:05:07,778 --> 01:05:09,614
<i>...end in nothing. Come home.

1239
01:05:10,324 --> 01:05:11,824
<i>I'll be here waiting and hoping...

1240
01:05:12,742 --> 01:05:13,409
...for every...

1241
01:05:13,577 --> 01:05:15,786
<i>...long dream of you to come true.

1242
01:05:16,204 --> 01:05:17,496
[TELEPHONE RINGS]

1243
01:05:19,750 --> 01:05:21,208
GATSBY:
Excuse me.

1244
01:05:28,467 --> 01:05:32,387
MAN: <i>Sir, Slagle's in Detroit.</i>
- I can't talk <i>now, old sport.

1245
01:05:34,597 --> 01:05:37,559
He must know what a small town is.

1246
01:05:37,768 --> 01:05:39,894
No, you listen to me. Listen to me.

1247
01:05:43,606 --> 01:05:45,608
I said a small town.

1248
01:05:46,443 --> 01:05:47,610
He must know what a small...

1249
01:05:47,818 --> 01:05:48,612
...town is.

1250
01:05:52,740 --> 01:05:55,744
Listen to me, he's of no use to us
if Detroit is his idea...

1251
01:05:55,952 --> 01:05:57,871
...of a small town, you understand?

1252
01:06:03,626 --> 01:06:05,545
We'll chat later, old sport.

1253
01:06:06,713 --> 01:06:08,090
All right.

1254
01:06:08,840 --> 01:06:10,634
[ORGAN PLAYING
UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC]

1255
01:06:11,802 --> 01:06:12,510
Klipspringer.

1256
01:06:14,679 --> 01:06:15,806
He must be awake.

1257
01:06:19,059 --> 01:06:20,268
Shall we?

1258
01:06:28,235 --> 01:06:29,193
DAISY:
Whoo!

1259
01:06:29,902 --> 01:06:30,862
NICK:
Ho!

1260
01:07:12,070 --> 01:07:15,657
I wish I'd done everything on earth with you.

1261
01:07:22,121 --> 01:07:23,831
All my life.

1262
01:07:26,626 --> 01:07:29,211
I wish it could always be like this.

1263
01:07:36,469 --> 01:07:38,262
It Will be.

1264
01:07:42,184 --> 01:07:45,478
<i>NICK:
If only it had been enough for Gatsby...

1265
01:07:45,686 --> 01:07:47,521
<i>...just to hold Daisy.

1266
01:07:47,688 --> 01:07:52,568
