Blue.

2019
01:48:33,632 --> 01:48:34,841
Right.

2020
01:48:35,009 --> 01:48:36,135
Here.

2021
01:48:37,136 --> 01:48:38,554
Leave us alone.

2022
01:48:39,889 --> 01:48:40,722
Wilson.

2023
01:48:45,144 --> 01:48:46,729
Who owns the yellow car?

2024
01:48:51,024 --> 01:48:52,859
A fella named Gatsby.

2025
01:48:53,235 --> 01:48:54,737
Jay Gatsby.

2026
01:48:56,154 --> 01:48:57,698
He's a crook, George.

2027
01:48:58,198 --> 01:49:01,243
Yes. Throws those parties
the papers are always talking about.

2028
01:49:07,832 --> 01:49:11,628
Maybe he was the one that was
fooling around with Myrtle.

2029
01:49:12,212 --> 01:49:12,921
[SOBS]
Maybe...

2030
01:49:13,088 --> 01:49:14,798
...that's why he killed her.

2031
01:49:14,966 --> 01:49:17,426
Yeah, maybe.

2032
01:49:18,677 --> 01:49:19,720
Guy like that, who knows?

2033
01:49:22,974 --> 01:49:26,018
He didn't have to kill her.

2034
01:49:35,903 --> 01:49:37,195
TOM:
Gatsby.

2035
01:49:38,989 --> 01:49:42,033
Something ought to be done
about a fella like that.

2036
01:49:44,912 --> 01:49:46,247
<i>He'll pay.

2037
01:49:47,289 --> 01:49:49,041
<i>Oh, he'll pay.

2038
01:49:55,672 --> 01:49:57,091
Coward.

2039
01:49:58,426 --> 01:50:00,469
He didn't even stop his car.

2040
01:50:02,721 --> 01:50:04,431
You gonna defend him now?

2041
01:50:05,307 --> 01:50:06,725
Huh?

2042
01:50:24,618 --> 01:50:26,287
TOM:
I'll telephone for a taxi, Nick.

2043
01:50:26,453 --> 01:50:28,497
Why don't you come inside
and have some supper...

2044
01:50:28,663 --> 01:50:29,372
...while you wait?

2045
01:50:29,539 --> 01:50:31,458
No, thanks. I'll wait outside.

2046
01:50:33,668 --> 01:50:34,545
What is the matter...

2047
01:50:34,712 --> 01:50:35,796
- . .With you?

2048
01:50:40,801 --> 01:50:41,844
Won't you come in, Nick?

2049
01:50:42,011 --> 01:50:43,011
No, thanks.

2050
01:50:43,179 --> 01:50:44,055
It's only half past 9.

2051
01:50:44,220 --> 01:50:45,180
No, I've had enough.

2052
01:50:45,805 --> 01:50:46,931
Of everyone.

2053
01:51:03,032 --> 01:51:04,699
GATSBY:
Hello, old sport.

2054
01:51:13,417 --> 01:51:14,835
NICK:
What are you doing?

2055
01:51:16,462 --> 01:51:17,921
GATSBY:
Just sitting here.

2056
01:51:18,088 --> 01:51:19,547
Yes, I see that.

2057
01:51:19,715 --> 01:51:21,509
You see any trouble out on the road?

2058
01:51:21,676 --> 01:51:22,426
That woman...

2059
01:51:22,592 --> 01:51:24,679
-...you ran down is dead, Jay.
- I thought so.

2060
01:51:24,929 --> 01:51:25,845
<i>L.

2061
01:51:26,012 --> 01:51:27,222
I told Daisy that I thought so.

2062
01:51:27,390 --> 01:51:29,350
Daisy? Do you hear yourself?

2063
01:51:29,516 --> 01:51:30,475
How could you?

2064
01:51:30,643 --> 01:51:31,560
How could you do that?

2065
01:51:31,726 --> 01:51:32,728
[WHISPERS]
Keep your voice down.

2066
01:51:32,895 --> 01:51:33,813
NICK:
You're nothing...

2067
01:51:33,979 --> 01:51:36,148
-...but a goddamn coward!
- Keep your voice down!

2068
01:51:36,314 --> 01:51:38,650
Please. There was no point in stop--

2069
01:51:38,818 --> 01:51:42,070
No point'? No point?
What about that woman?

2070
01:51:42,238 --> 01:51:44,614
No point. She was killed instantly.

2071
01:51:44,782 --> 01:51:46,617
Yes, it ripped her open!
I was there! I saw her!

2072
01:51:46,783 --> 01:51:49,828
I understand! I understand! It was my fault.

2073
01:51:49,994 --> 01:51:51,247
It was my fault. This woman...

2074
01:51:51,413 --> 01:51:55,208
...she rushed out at us
as if she was trying to speak to us.

2075
01:51:55,376 --> 01:51:58,921
It all happened so quickly.
She tried-- I tried...

2076
01:51:59,087 --> 01:52:00,131
-...to turn in time...
-"She"?

2077
01:52:00,296 --> 01:52:01,506
...but--

2078
01:52:18,481 --> 01:52:19,692
It was Daisy.

2079
01:52:25,113 --> 01:52:26,698
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Well, I...

2080
01:52:29,243 --> 01:52:33,538
You see, after we left New York,
she was very nervous.

2081
01:52:33,706 --> 01:52:37,001
She thought that driving would steady her.

2082
01:52:38,502 --> 01:52:41,130
But this woman, she rushed...

2083
01:52:41,296 --> 01:52:42,506
<i>...out at us.

2084
01:52:44,800 --> 01:52:45,592
It all happened so quickly.

2085
01:52:47,677 --> 01:52:48,636
It wasn't her fault...

2086
01:52:48,804 --> 01:52:49,846
<i>...do you see?

2087
01:53:11,409 --> 01:53:14,371
No one must know that Daisy was driving.

2088
01:53:15,706 --> 01:53:16,707
Promise me.

2089
01:53:18,375 --> 01:53:21,670
Jay, you should go home
and get some rest.

2090
01:53:21,837 --> 01:53:24,881
I'm going to wait here.
I'm going to wait here all night...

2091
01:53:25,048 --> 01:53:26,216
-...if necessary.
- No, no, no.

2092
01:53:26,382 --> 01:53:27,801
- That's not a good idea.
- If he tries...

2093
01:53:27,967 --> 01:53:30,429
...to bother her about that
unpleasantness this afternoon...

2094
01:53:30,595 --> 01:53:31,639
If he tries to bother her...

2095
01:53:32,222 --> 01:53:34,682
If he tries any brutality on her whatsoever--

2096
01:53:34,850 --> 01:53:37,019
Torn won't touch her.
He's not even thinking about her.

2097
01:53:37,185 --> 01:53:38,979
I don't trust him.

2098
01:53:39,145 --> 01:53:41,815
- I don't trust him.
- All right.

2099
01:53:42,274 --> 01:53:42,942
All right.

2100
01:53:46,487 --> 01:53:47,863
You wait here.

2101
01:53:49,364 --> 01:53:50,783
I'll see if there's any commotion.

2102
01:53:52,326 --> 01:53:53,452
Would you?

2103
01:53:58,289 --> 01:54:00,042
Thank you, old sport.

2104
01:54:06,506 --> 01:54:09,051
TOM: Listen, she was in the wrong,
running out on the road.

2105
01:54:09,844 --> 01:54:11,220
Sweetheart, you have...

2106
01:54:11,386 --> 01:54:12,762
...nothing to worry about.

2107
01:54:12,930 --> 01:54:15,181
Let me take care of things.

2108
01:54:15,349 --> 01:54:16,850
Take care of you.

2109
01:54:17,100 --> 01:54:18,644
I'll make some calls.

2110
01:54:18,810 --> 01:54:20,645
We'll go away.

2111
01:54:21,354 --> 01:54:23,690
Just go away, get out of town.

2112
01:54:24,315 --> 01:54:25,984
Get some rest. Don't worry.

2113
01:54:26,860 --> 01:54:28,904
It'll be all right.

2114
01:54:31,073 --> 01:54:32,408
Hey-

2115
01:54:42,667 --> 01:54:44,252
[CAR APPROACHES]

2116
01:55:00,060 --> 01:55:03,188
Oh. Hello, old sport.

2117
01:55:03,439 --> 01:55:04,439
J8)'-

2118
01:55:05,231 --> 01:55:06,817
- Everything all right?
- Yes.

2119
01:55:07,568 --> 01:55:09,235
Everything's just fine.

2120
01:55:09,737 --> 01:55:12,989
Around 4:00, she came to the window.

2121
01:55:13,823 --> 01:55:15,492
She stood there, then...

2122
01:55:16,827 --> 01:55:18,996
Then she turned out the light, so...

2123
01:55:19,662 --> 01:55:20,872
Well...

2124
01:55:22,207 --> 01:55:24,251
Give me a hand, will you, old sport?

2125
01:55:24,960 --> 01:55:28,421
<i>NICK: I should have told him
what I had just seen, but...

2126
01:55:29,381 --> 01:55:30,757
<i>...all I could manage was:

2127
01:55:32,134 --> 01:55:34,094
You know, Jay,
with everything that's happened...

2128
01:55:34,261 --> 01:55:35,845
...you ought to go away.

2129
01:55:36,012 --> 01:55:37,430
Tonight. They'll trace your car.

2130
01:55:37,597 --> 01:55:39,515
Go away? No, I can't leave now.

2131
01:55:39,682 --> 01:55:40,684
Not tonight.

2132
01:55:40,850 --> 01:55:42,936
Jay, do you understand
that a woman has been killed?

2133
01:55:43,103 --> 01:55:44,771
Daisy's going to call in the morning.

2134
01:55:45,271 --> 01:55:48,108
Then we'll make plans
to go away together.

2135
01:55:50,152 --> 01:55:51,444
- Yeah.
- Daisy, she--

2136
01:55:51,612 --> 01:55:53,863
She just needs time
to think things through. Herzog...

2137
01:55:54,030 --> 01:55:55,865
...we're talking. Thank you.

2138
01:56:00,037 --> 01:56:01,956
She just needs time to think.

2139
01:56:02,122 --> 01:56:04,582
No, Jay. With Daisy--

2140
01:56:04,875 --> 01:56:09,712
She just needs time to think.
She's going to call in the morning.

2141
01:56:17,971 --> 01:56:18,639
Wait up with me.

2142
01:56:24,103 --> 01:56:25,145
The sun's almost up.

2143
01:56:29,649 --> 01:56:32,903
<i>NICK: That was the night
he finally told me the truth.

2144
01:56:33,069 --> 01:56:34,320
<i>All of it.

2145
01:56:37,323 --> 01:56:39,909
GATSBY:
You know, I've thought for a while...

2146
01:56:40,077 --> 01:56:44,872
...I had a lot of things,
but the truth is I'm empty.

2147
01:56:45,039 --> 01:56:47,960
I suppose that's why
I make things up about myself.

2148
01:56:48,127 --> 01:56:50,921
But I've wanted to tell you
the whole story for...

2149
01:56:51,087 --> 01:56:52,506
...a very long time.

2150
01:56:53,673 --> 01:56:56,635
See, I grew up terribly, terribly poor,
old sport.

2151
01:56:56,844 --> 01:57:00,180
<i>- My folks were...
NICK: He revealed his humble beginnings...

2152
01:57:00,346 --> 01:57:03,559
<i>...his transformative voyage
with Dan Cody...

2153
01:57:03,725 --> 01:57:06,353
<i>...the war, Oxford...

2154
01:57:06,520 --> 01:57:09,814
<i>...and how he joined Wolfshiem
in the business.

2155
01:57:11,233 --> 01:57:12,693
<i>It was also that night...

2156
01:57:12,859 --> 01:57:16,947
<i>...that I became aware of Gatsby's
extraordinary gift for hope.

2157
01:57:17,113 --> 01:57:20,158
I can't describe how surprised I was
to find out that I loved her.

2158
01:57:20,324 --> 01:57:21,452
And that she loved me too.

2159
01:57:21,618 --> 01:57:24,579
<i>NICK: A gift that I have never found
in any other person.

2160
01:57:24,747 --> 01:57:27,332
I never realized how extraordinary...

2161
01:57:27,498 --> 01:57:29,417
...a nice girl could be.

2162
01:57:29,585 --> 01:57:33,130
<i>And which it is not likely
I shall ever find again.

2163
01:57:33,296 --> 01:57:35,173
I thought out my life with Daisy in it...

2164
01:57:35,340 --> 01:57:38,635
...trying to figure out how we could marry
and struggle along on so many dollars a month.

2165
01:57:40,720 --> 01:57:42,472
What was in the letter?

2166
01:57:45,059 --> 01:57:49,645
The reason why after the war
I hadn't been able to return.

2167
01:57:50,314 --> 01:57:54,568
I asked her to wait until I made
something of myself, but she was...

2168
01:57:56,319 --> 01:57:58,613
See, I felt married to her.

2169
01:58:01,533 --> 01:58:02,868
That was all.

2170
01:58:03,786 --> 01:58:05,203
<i>NICK:
It was all for her.

2171
01:58:05,662 --> 01:58:07,872
<i>The house, the parties.

2172
01:58:08,039 --> 01:58:09,207
<i>Everything.

2173
01:58:16,715 --> 01:58:18,634
<i>WILSON:
God sees everything.

2174
01:58:27,559 --> 01:58:29,520
HERZOG:
Mr. Gatsby, sir, excuse me.

2175
01:58:29,936 --> 01:58:31,479
Chicago calling, sir.

2176
01:58:31,646 --> 01:58:32,898
Not now.

2177
01:58:33,564 --> 01:58:36,318
Keep it open for a personal call.

2178
01:58:36,902 --> 01:58:39,863
HERZOG: A personal call? Of course.
GARDENER: Excuse me, sir.

2179
01:58:40,029 --> 01:58:41,573
Mr. Gatsby, I'm gonna drain the pool.

2180
01:58:41,739 --> 01:58:43,617
Before the leaves start falling in.

2181
01:58:43,783 --> 01:58:45,243
Not today.

2182
01:58:47,871 --> 01:58:49,872
Not today, it's so beautiful.

2183
01:58:50,998 --> 01:58:56,337
You know, old sport, I haven't used that
pool once all summer. Let's take a swim.

2184
01:58:57,756 --> 01:58:59,632
Have the phone brought down to the pool.

2185
01:59:13,604 --> 01:59:15,356
I have to go, Jay.

2186
01:59:18,025 --> 01:59:19,444
I have to work.

2187
01:59:19,944 --> 01:59:21,363
I understand.

2188
01:59:23,073 --> 01:59:24,323
Well...

2189
01:59:24,490 --> 01:59:26,033
...I'll walk you out.

2190
01:59:33,708 --> 01:59:36,502
Well, I'll call you up.

2191
01:59:36,712 --> 01:59:39,172
Please do, old sport. Please do.

2192
01:59:42,009 --> 01:59:42,717
I supposed.

2193
01:59:42,885 --> 01:59:44,677
...that Daisy will call too.

2194
01:59:48,472 --> 01:59:49,932
<i>L.

2195
01:59:51,018 --> 01:59:52,310
I suppose.

2196
01:59:53,436 --> 01:59:54,563
Yes.

2197
01:59:56,773 --> 01:59:58,692
Well, goodbye.

2198
02:00:17,543 --> 02:00:18,795
NICK:
Jay!

2199
02:00:20,963 --> 02:00:22,506
They're a rotten crowd.

2200
02:00:24,592 --> 02:00:27,304
You're worth the whole
damn bunch put together.

2201
02:00:37,271 --> 02:00:38,314
<i>NICK:
I was always glad...

2202
02:00:38,481 --> 02:00:39,733
<i>...I said that.

2203
02:00:41,984 --> 02:00:42,735
<i>It was the only...

2204
02:00:42,903 --> 02:00:44,363
<i>...compliment I ever paid him.

2205
02:00:48,617 --> 02:00:49,618
<i>That morning...

2206
02:00:50,368 --> 02:00:52,662
<i>...Wall Street boomed its usual...

2207
02:00:52,828 --> 02:00:53,997
<i>...golden roar.

2208
02:00:54,163 --> 02:00:57,960
<i>But I wasn't worth a decent stroke of work.

2209
02:00:58,877 --> 02:01:01,837
<i>I waited for Gatsby to call with news.

2210
02:01:04,298 --> 02:01:05,967
<i>While he waited...

2211
02:01:06,134 --> 02:01:07,469
...for Daisy.

2212
02:01:32,159 --> 02:01:33,828
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

2213
02:01:49,845 --> 02:01:51,345
HERZOG:
Gatsby's.

2214
02:01:52,764 --> 02:01:55,975
I know Mr. Gatsby will be
very happy that you've called.

2215
02:01:56,143 --> 02:01:57,476
[GUNSHOT]

2216
02:02:18,414 --> 02:02:20,167
Daisy.

2217
02:02:39,310 --> 02:02:40,686
[GUNSHOT]

2218
02:02:41,520 --> 02:02:43,899
Hello! Hello!

2219
02:02:44,065 --> 02:02:46,568
<i>Hello! ls everything all right?

2220
02:02:52,323 --> 02:02:55,077
Hello! Hello!

2221
02:02:55,243 --> 02:02:56,619
Hello!

2222
02:02:56,787 --> 02:02:58,829
<i>Hello! ls everything all right?

2223
02:03:08,965 --> 02:03:13,177
<i>NICK: I remember the rest of that day
as an endless drill...

2224
02:03:13,345 --> 02:03:17,974
...of <i>police and photographers
and tabloid reporters.

2225
02:03:18,682 --> 02:03:20,935
<i>The headlines were a nightmare.

2226
02:03:22,104 --> 02:03:24,146
<i>They pinned everything on Gatsby.

2227
02:03:24,314 --> 02:03:28,693
<i>The affair with Myrtle.
The hit-and-run. Everything.

2228
02:03:28,902 --> 02:03:30,904
<i>And there was nothing I could say...

2229
02:03:31,070 --> 02:03:36,118
<i>...except the one unutterable fact
that none of it was true.

2230
02:03:36,451 --> 02:03:39,912
DAISY: Darling, Daddy's taking care
of his two favorite girls.

2231
02:03:40,079 --> 02:03:41,288
PAMMY:
Where are we going?

2232
02:03:41,832 --> 02:03:43,792
- We're going on a holiday.
TOM: We should go.

2233
02:03:43,958 --> 02:03:45,252
DAISY:
Just you...

2234
02:03:45,418 --> 02:03:47,002
...me and Daddy.

2235
02:03:47,170 --> 02:03:48,671
[TELEPHONE RINGING]

2236
02:03:49,338 --> 02:03:50,590
Buchanan residence.

2237
02:03:50,756 --> 02:03:52,175
NICK:
May I speak to Mrs. Buchanan?

2238
02:03:52,634 --> 02:03:54,136
It's Mr. Carraway, her cousin.

2239
02:03:54,301 --> 02:03:54,970
<i>HENRY.
Madame...

2240
02:03:55,136 --> 02:03:57,012
...is not available, Monsieur Carraway.

2241
02:03:57,471 --> 02:04:00,350
If you speak to her,
tell her the funeral's tomorrow.

2242
02:04:00,516 --> 02:04:02,476
I'm sorry, monsieur,
they have gone away.

2243
02:04:02,644 --> 02:04:03,478
<i>Gone away?

2244
02:04:03,936 --> 02:04:05,479
Do you know when they'll be back?

2245
02:04:08,149 --> 02:04:09,024
No.

2246
02:04:09,192 --> 02:04:11,153
<i>They have already departed.

2247
02:04:15,114 --> 02:04:19,368
Please. I know that she would
want to be there. She would--

2248
02:04:19,578 --> 02:04:21,454
If you would just get a message to her.

2249
02:04:21,621 --> 02:04:24,832
<i>- Let</i> me talk to her, <i>please.</i>
HENRI: You wish to contact her?

2250
02:04:25,625 --> 02:04:27,461
I have no further information, monsieur.

2251
02:04:27,836 --> 02:04:29,003
Please!

2252
02:04:29,171 --> 02:04:30,296
[HENRI SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

2253
02:04:31,756 --> 02:04:33,091
Hello?

2254
02:04:40,015 --> 02:04:41,224
TOM:
Come on.

2255
02:04:41,975 --> 02:04:44,394
<i>NICK:
They were careless people, Tom and Daisy.

2256
02:04:46,104 --> 02:04:48,273
<i>They smashed up things and people...

2257
02:04:48,439 --> 02:04:51,109
<i>...and then retreated back
into their money and their...

2258
02:04:51,275 --> 02:04:52,985
<i>...vast carelessness.

2259
02:04:54,695 --> 02:04:55,947
Hey-

2260
02:04:56,113 --> 02:04:57,782
Hey! Get out of here!

2261
02:04:58,240 --> 02:04:59,493
Go on!

2262
02:04:59,658 --> 02:05:01,203
Get the hell out of here!

2263
02:05:14,925 --> 02:05:16,176
NICK:
<i>I</i> rang...

2264
02:05:16,342 --> 02:05:17,927
...I wrote...

2265
02:05:18,094 --> 02:05:20,095
<i>...I implored.

2266
02:05:20,680 --> 02:05:26,019
<i>But not a single one of the sparkling
hundreds that enjoyed his hospitality...

2267
02:05:26,895 --> 02:05:29,396
<i>...attended the funeral.

2268
02:05:29,855 --> 02:05:31,649
<i>And from Daisy...

2269
02:05:32,359 --> 02:05:34,319
<i>...not even a flower.

2270
02:05:36,029 --> 02:05:38,364
<i>I was all he had.

2271
02:05:38,948 --> 02:05:41,368
<i>The only one who cared.

2272
02:06:12,481 --> 02:06:14,568
<i>After Gatsby's death...

2273
02:06:15,527 --> 02:06:17,988
<i>...New York was haunted for me.

2274
02:06:19,154 --> 02:06:20,532
<i>That city...

2275
02:06:22,492 --> 02:06:26,203
<i>...my once golden shimmering mirage...

2276
02:06:27,663 --> 02:06:29,873
<i>...now made me sick.

2277
02:06:33,502 --> 02:06:34,378
<i>On my last night...

2278
02:06:34,546 --> 02:06:35,963
...in New York...

2279
02:06:36,965 --> 02:06:38,882
<i>...I returned to that huge...

2280
02:06:39,050 --> 02:06:41,927
<i>...incoherent house once more.

2281
02:06:42,095 --> 02:06:43,470
<i>Wolfshiem's associates...

2282
02:06:43,637 --> 02:06:45,140
<i>...had cleaned it out.

2283
02:06:45,306 --> 02:06:46,682
<i>JORDAN".
He threw all those parties...

2284
02:06:46,850 --> 02:06:48,560
<i>...hoping she'd wander in one night.

2285
02:06:48,726 --> 02:06:50,060
NICK:
It's like an amusement park.

2286
02:06:50,228 --> 02:06:52,146
<i>DAISY:
But how do you live here all alone?

2287
02:06:52,314 --> 02:06:54,524
GATSBY:
She makes it look so splendid...

2288
02:06:54,690 --> 02:06:55,859
...don't you think, old sport?

2289
02:06:56,025 --> 02:06:57,944
DAISY:
Music! And then we can...

2290
02:06:58,110 --> 02:06:59,738
...dance all night!

2291
02:07:01,530 --> 02:07:02,823
<i>GATSBY:
Will you come, old sport?

2292
02:07:02,990 --> 02:07:04,117
<i>We need you.

2293
02:07:04,283 --> 02:07:06,411
DAISY:
I wish it could always be like this.

2294
02:07:06,578 --> 02:07:08,246
It Will be.

2295
02:07:10,039 --> 02:07:15,377
<i>NICK: I remembered how we had all come to
Gatsby's and guessed at his corruption...

2296
02:07:16,503 --> 02:07:18,547
<i>...while he stood before</i> us...

2297
02:07:18,715 --> 02:07:19,381
<i>...concealing...

2298
02:07:19,548 --> 02:07:22,092
<i>...an incorruptible dream.

2299
02:07:23,094 --> 02:07:28,015
<i>DAISY: It's perfect. From your perfect,
irresistible imagination.

2300
02:07:34,104 --> 02:07:35,939
<i>NICK:
The moon rose higher.

2301
02:07:37,650 --> 02:07:40,862
<i>And as I stood there,
brooding on the old, unknown world...

2302
02:07:41,904 --> 02:07:43,948
<i>...I thought of Gatsby's wonder...

2303
02:07:44,114 --> 02:07:47,868
<i>...when he first picked out the green light
at the end of Daisy's dock.

2304
02:07:53,457 --> 02:07:55,793
<i>He had come such a long way.

2305
02:07:56,586 --> 02:07:59,046
<i>And his dream
must have seemed so close...

2306
02:07:59,213 --> 02:08:02,175
<i>...that he could hardly fail to grasp it.

2307
02:08:06,512 --> 02:08:07,639
<i>But he did not know...

2308
02:08:07,805 --> 02:08:09,932
<i>...that it was already behind him.

2309
02:08:11,768 --> 02:08:14,729
<i>Gatsby believed in the green light...

2310
02:08:14,938 --> 02:08:18,315
<i>...the orgastic future
that year by year recedes...

2311
02:08:18,483 --> 02:08:19,609
<i>...before us.

2312
02:08:19,775 --> 02:08:22,529
<i>It eluded us then, but that's no matter.

2313
02:08:22,904 --> 02:08:25,657
<i>Tomorrow, we will run faster...

2314
02:08:25,823 --> 02:08:28,368
<i>...stretch out our arms farther...

2315
02:08:28,827 --> 02:08:31,371
<i>...and one fine morning...

2316
02:08:31,537 --> 02:08:33,622
<i>So we beat on...

2317
02:08:34,082 --> 02:08:36,417
<i>...boats against the current...

2318
02:08:37,001 --> 02:08:38,752
<i>...borne back...

2319
02:08:38,920 --> 02:08:40,755
<i>...ceaselessly...

2320
02:08:41,131 --> 02:08:43,173
<i>...into the past.

